Configure Bluetooth via the Local Group Policy Editor

Press Win + R to launch Run, type gpedit.msc, and press Ctrl + Shift + Enter.

Go to Computer Configuration > Administrative Templates > Network > Bluetooth.

Inside Bluetooth, double-click Turn off the Bluetooth user experience.

Set the policy to Enabled to hide the Bluetooth UI and prevent its usage. Set the policy to Disabled to reverse the change above.

Optionally, you can go to services.msc to prevent the Bluetooth stack from running.
Press Win + R to open Run, type services.msc, and then press Enter.
Find Bluetooth Support Service, right-click, and select Properties.
Under the General tab, click the Startup type dropdown menu, and choose Disabled.
This stops Bluetooth processes in the background, preventing users from re-enabling it.
Click Stop, Apply, and then OK



